The LOA describes the likelihood that the larva in a particular location would move. Its value might be different in different strains. The LOA difference between different strains (dLOA) was deduced by the following formula, using the comparison between TL and AB strains in the same location as an example:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$LOA(TL)-LOA(AB)={\beta }_{s}^{(TL)}-{\beta }_{s}^{(AB)}+({\beta }_{{I}_{1}}^{(TL)}-{\beta }_{{I}_{1}}^{(AB)})t+({\beta }_{{I}_{2}}^{(TL)}-{\beta }_{{I}_{2}}^{(AB)}){t}^{2}.$$\end{document}LOA(TL)−LOA(AB)=βs(TL)−βs(AB)+(βI1(TL)−βI1(AB))t+(βI2(TL)−βI2(AB))t2.

Since the other basic effects were the same between the two strains at time t, they canceled each other. The random effects (γ
i) also canceled each other for the same location. The first part of the formula, \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
