				\begin{document}$$({\rm{i}}.{\rm{e}}.\,{\rm{at}}\,t=1)$$\end{document}(i.e.att=1), there was no significant difference between TL and TLAB larvae. Their LOAs increased by 0.6076 and 0.8342 respectively when compared with that of AB. This can be due to the SNPs in the TL line were associated with dominant genes for higher locomotor activities. The hybrid TLAB line would therefore still display the dominant active phenotype. The second part of strain effect on LOA was in its interaction with time. The dLOA between TL and TLAB had a significant linear pattern over time (2.1698, p < 0.0001); whereas the dLOA between TLAB and AB strains had significant linear (−3.0496, p < 0.0001) and quadratic patterns (−7.9245, p = 0.0330) over time. This trend was also shown by the predicted probability of WT strains that moved during the same time interval (Fig. 1, middle panel). When TL and TLAB strains were exposed to a Light-On stimulus, more of them tended to move compared to AB. TLAB larvae, however, returned to the baseline activity faster than AB and TL larvae, as the proportion of moving TLAB larvae decreased faster than that of AB and TL.Table 1
